  "stage": {
    "id": "foundations",
    "stageNumber": 1,
    "title": "Optimization Foundations",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "sgd",
        "title": "Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD)",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Mini-batch gradient computation\n- Parameter updates proportional to gradients\n- Foundation of all modern optimizers\n\nSGD is the workhorse of deep learning. Instead of computing gradients on the entire dataset (which would be prohibitively expensive), SGD takes random mini-batches and updates parameters based on those noisy gradient estimates. This stochasticity actually helps escape local minima! The update rule is simple: θ = θ - α∇L, where α is the learning rate and ∇L is the gradient. Think of it like hiking downhill in fog—you can't see the entire valley, but you can feel the slope under your feet and take a step downward.",
        "position": {
          "x": 3,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "momentum",
        "title": "Momentum: Accelerating Convergence",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Velocity vector accumulation\n- Acceleration in consistent directions\n- Damping of oscillations\n\nMomentum is like pushing a ball down a hill. Even if the terrain gets bumpy, the ball keeps rolling in the same direction because it has accumulated energy. In optimization, we track a velocity vector v that accumulates gradients: v = βv + ∇L. At each step, we move in the direction of v rather than just the current gradient. This helps us move faster on consistent downhill slopes while damping out noisy oscillations—especially useful in deep neural networks where the landscape can be quite chaotic.",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "adagrad",
        "title": "AdaGrad: Adaptive Learning Rates",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Per-parameter adaptive rates\n- Accumulated squared gradients\n- Better for sparse data\n\nAdaGrad is clever: it divides the learning rate by the square root of accumulated squared gradients for each parameter. Why? Parameters with large, consistent gradients get smaller effective learning rates (they're already making progress), while parameters with small gradients get larger rates (they need more encouragement). This is especially useful for sparse problems like NLP where some parameters appear in many examples while others are rare. However, AdaGrad has a fatal flaw: the accumulated sum never decreases, so learning rates eventually vanish.",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "rmsprop",
        "title": "RMSprop: The Adaptive Learning Rate Fixed",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Exponential moving average instead of cumsum\n- Adaptive without vanishing rates\n- Maintains long-term stability\n\nRMSprop fixes AdaGrad's dying learning rate problem by using an exponential moving average: v = βv + (1-β)∇L². Only recent gradients matter—old ones fade exponentially. Think of it like a leaky bucket: new water (recent gradients) comes in, but old water (old gradients) leaks out. This keeps the learning rates stable and prevents them from shrinking to zero. β is typically 0.999, so the effective 'window' of history is about 1000 iterations.",
        "position": {
          "x": 15,
          "y": 6
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-1",
      "question": "How does RMSprop improve upon AdaGrad? Answer with a number.",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "It uses a running average of squared gradients instead of accumulating them forever",
        "It reduces memory requirements",
        "Both of the above"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "It uses a running average of squared gradients instead of accumulating them forever",
